a. Docker – Introduction
❑In recent years, a particular technology has attracted attention
in the market, on social networks and at events, namely Docker. ❑Docker is an open source containerization tool from 2013,
which allows isolating applications from the server system. ▪Helps applications become mobile, can be tested on the developer's
workstation and deployed to the production environment without
worrying about runtime dependencies. ▪It is a cross -platform tool, can be installed on Windows, Linux,
macOS, ...and is available by default on some cloud providers such as
AWS, Azure, ... University of Information and Communication
Technology

Container
A system that embeds the application with its dependencies, containing only a lightweight operating system and
the necessary elements. Comparison with VM
Unlike virtual machines (VMs) that contain a full operating system, containers rely on the guest operating system
(the container only contains a lightweight operating system (OS) and the elements necessary for that operating
system such as system libraries, binary files and code dependencies). Portability
Docker makes applications portable by building images that are easy to deploy across different environments
without compatibility issues. University of Information and Communication
Technologya. Docker – Introduction

❑To operate,  Docker  needs  the following  elements :
▪Docker  Desktop  UI: manage  containers
▪Docker  client : Is a command  line tool (docker)  that you
use to give commands,  for example : docker  run, docker
build,  ... ▪Docker  daemon : Is the "engine"  of Docker,  responsible
for: Managing  containers,  images,  networks,  volumes ;
Executing  commands  from  the Docker  Client . ▪Docker  Registry : This is a public  repository  (Docker  Hub)
or a private  repository  of Docker  images  (account
registration  required)
In Docker Desktop, Docker Client and Docker Daemon are
available → run directly on Desktop (Windows /Mac/Linux). Docker Desktop only connects to Docker Hub by default
